quran[13]{c,v,t,f}:
  43,61,"And indeed he{1}is a portent of the Hour, so never be<sup>pl </sup>skeptical about it and follow Me; this is a straight path.",1:[Referring to Jesus, son of Mary.]
  43,62,"And let not Satan bar you<sup>pl </sup>; indeed, he is an evident enemy to you."
  43,63,"And when Jesus came with the evident proofs, he said, “I have come to you<sup>pl </sup>with wisdom, and to clarify for you some of what you differ over, so be mindful of Allah and obey me."
  43,64,"Indeed, Allah is my Lord and your Lord, so worship Him; this is a straight path.”"
  43,65,"But the parties differed among themselves, so woe to those who committed injustices from the punishment of a painful day."
  43,66,"Are they only waiting for the Hour to come upon them suddenly, while they are unaware?"
  43,67,"On that day, close friends will be enemies to one another, except for the ones who were mindful<i>(of God) </i>."
  43,68,"O My servants, no fear shall be upon you today, nor shall you grieve."
  43,69,"Those who believed in Our signs{1}and were Muslims{2}:",1:[The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Quran, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.],2:[A Muslim is one who is submissive to Allah.]
  43,70,"enter the Garden<i>(of Paradise) </i>, you and your spouses, filled up with joy."
  43,71,"They are served around with trays of gold and cups, and therein is whatever is desired{1}by the selvesand delights the eyes, and therein you<sup>pl </sup>abide.",1:[Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Amer, Hafs and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…whatever the selves desire and delights the eyes…”]
  43,72,"And that is the Garden<i>(of Paradise) </i>you<sup>pl </sup>were made{1}to inherit on account of what you used to do.",1:[Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered upon by the reader.]
  43,73,"For you<sup>pl </sup>therein is abundant fruit from which you eat."
